100:00:00,000 --> 00:00:11,280I have a daughter who is 13 years old, but in 2012, when it was the financial collapse200:00:11,280 --> 00:00:15,960that dropped all the bags in the world and all that, I had five less than I would now have300:00:15,960 --> 00:00:17,960Eight, nine years.400:00:17,960 --> 00:00:23,680And we were watching the news, we were having lunch watching the news, and it showed up.500:00:23,680 --> 00:00:28,720a kind of bald tie, a journalist who always gave bad news, was the one who600:00:03,760 --> 00:00:09,240And that day he said, last minute, the bag collapsed all over the world.700:00:09,240 --> 00:00:10,680And my daughter looked at me.800:00:10,680 --> 00:00:16,640And I got pale and followed the guy and the nominal value of the bonus went off.900:00:16,640 --> 00:00:19,840for not being able to sustain debt obligations.1000:00:19,840 --> 00:00:22,080And my daughter was looking at me.1100:00:22,080 --> 00:00:24,400Investment banking collapsed, the guy said.1200:00:24,400 --> 00:00:26,080Shareholders are killing themselves.1300:00:26,080 --> 00:00:29,240And my daughter opened her big eyes, so did I.1400:00:03,160 --> 00:00:07,160Obviously I got scared, because something serious was going on, and then Nina, my daughter, who always wondered what the tsunami was,1500:00:07,160 --> 00:00:09,880what is the plane that fell, and it was easy to explain it from the tsunami,1600:00:09,880 --> 00:00:13,720It's the epicenter of a thing at sea that Filipinos then die.1700:00:13,720 --> 00:00:15,480It's simple.1800:00:15,480 --> 00:00:19,320He asked me, what is this that happened now, Dad? Is it serious?1900:00:19,320 --> 00:00:25,320And I realized I had no idea how to explain it to a guy.2000:00:25,320 --> 00:00:26,720What a thing that was.2100:00:26,720 --> 00:00:29,560An earthquake is easy to explain, but how do you explain it to a baby?2200:00:02,800 --> 00:00:06,000You can't explain it to him because it's intangible more than anything.2300:00:06,000 --> 00:00:10,920But since I'm a headmaster and in free time I'm a writer too,2400:00:10,920 --> 00:00:15,640I set out to do it, so I wrote a story, a children's story,2500:00:15,640 --> 00:00:18,760And the next day, when we were looking back at the news2600:00:18,760 --> 00:00:21,600And he asked me again what I did was to tell him a story.2700:00:21,600 --> 00:00:24,280I want to share with you.2800:00:24,280 --> 00:00:29,560I tell you, I told Nina that day that there was once a very quiet town2900:00:03,240 --> 00:00:06,280and that there was a boy named Pepe, the protagonist, who lived in the furthest house from the village.3000:00:06,280 --> 00:00:10,040One afternoon, Pepe went for a walk and got thirsty.3100:00:10,040 --> 00:00:12,680When he came home, he opened a bottle of wine,3200:00:12,680 --> 00:00:15,800And while he was drinking wine, he discovered one thing.3300:00:15,800 --> 00:00:18,400that no one had ever discovered.3400:00:18,400 --> 00:00:22,120There were no bars in town, there wasn't a bar.3500:00:22,120 --> 00:00:24,480Pepe thought if I opened a bar,3600:00:24,480 --> 00:00:27,800I could make others happy by giving them to drink,3700:00:03,440 --> 00:00:07,120And besides, he also thought he could win some currency, and he was happy with the idea of opening a bar.3800:00:07,120 --> 00:00:10,140That afternoon his friend Moncho stopped by Pepe's house.3900:00:10,140 --> 00:00:13,340and gave him a good name for the bar.4000:00:13,340 --> 00:00:16,620And you know, when an old-fashioned idea has a name,4100:00:16,620 --> 00:00:19,960You're starting to walk that idea.4200:00:19,960 --> 00:00:22,260So Pepe made a list of needs.4300:00:22,260 --> 00:00:24,260to open the first bar in town.4400:00:24,260 --> 00:00:26,320Nina was looking at me with her eyes open.4500:00:26,320 --> 00:00:28,760The story was fine so far.4600:00:03,440 --> 00:00:07,960Pepe realized that since he bought tables, chairs, glasses, paint, a palenque so that the customers of the bar would put their horses4700:00:07,960 --> 00:00:09,640and they could come in and drink,4800:00:09,640 --> 00:00:13,920And he took out the bills and all that was gonna cost him about 10,000 coins.4900:00:13,920 --> 00:00:17,280Of course, Pepe didn't have 10,000 coins because he was poor,5000:00:17,280 --> 00:00:21,880But during the night he came up with a way to get those 10,000 coins.5100:00:21,880 --> 00:00:24,720Pepe cut a thousand pieces of paper.5200:00:02,880 --> 00:00:05,380and wrote on every little paper the phrase, soon Bar de Pepe.5300:00:05,380 --> 00:00:07,480A thousand times he wrote that.5400:00:07,480 --> 00:00:11,000And on Sunday after Mass he went to the People's Square,5500:00:11,000 --> 00:00:12,800dressed in his best suit,5600:00:12,800 --> 00:00:16,380and said to all the neighbors in the Plaza,5700:00:16,380 --> 00:00:20,140Dear neighbors, I'm opening a bar on the outskirts of town.5800:00:20,140 --> 00:00:21,580Everyone looked at him.5900:00:21,580 --> 00:00:23,480“What a good idea!” some said.6000:00:23,480 --> 00:00:25,980Pepe felt great with everyone's attention.6100:00:25,980 --> 00:00:28,000and then it showed in fan6200:00:03,400 --> 00:00:06,840the thousand small pieces of paper cut and said, this is important, Nina I told her, Pepe said,6300:00:06,840 --> 00:00:10,600each of these thousand small pieces of paper costs 10 coins,6400:00:10,600 --> 00:00:12,800The neighbors looked at him.6500:00:12,800 --> 00:00:16,040Whoever buys me a little piece of paper is gonna have to keep it.6600:00:16,040 --> 00:00:19,080Because in a month's time, when I open my bar,6700:00:19,080 --> 00:00:22,720I'm gonna pay 12 coins for every little piece of paper.6800:00:22,720 --> 00:00:25,120I want you guys to give me back.6900:00:25,120 --> 00:00:27,480Then there were whispers all over the square7000:00:03,760 --> 00:00:06,440And Moncho, who was the fool of the people, asked, for Pepe, but it does not cost 10 coins each paper,7100:00:06,440 --> 00:00:09,280Why are you going to give away two more coins later?7200:00:09,280 --> 00:00:12,560And Pepe said, it's not a gift, Moncho, it's a reward.7300:00:12,560 --> 00:00:15,360I'll make it up to two more coins.7400:00:15,360 --> 00:00:19,120to those who help me fulfill my dream, which is to open a bar.7500:00:19,120 --> 00:00:22,560So the mayor who was out there came up and said,7600:00:22,560 --> 00:00:26,280Makes sense, makes a lot of sense, all right, Pepe.7700:00:04,260 --> 00:00:06,720And Ernesto, who was rich and understood business, said, to me the idea sounds very good.7800:00:06,720 --> 00:00:10,640And priest Ricardo, pulling some coins from below his cassock,7900:00:10,640 --> 00:00:13,940He said, it's a very Christian idea.8000:00:13,940 --> 00:00:16,820I want some of your little papers,8100:00:16,820 --> 00:00:20,820And they all started buying Pepe's little papers.8200:00:20,820 --> 00:00:24,480In that simple way and in a single morning,8300:00:24,480 --> 00:00:26,660Pepe got the money to open his bar.8400:00:26,660 --> 00:00:29,640Among all the neighbors they bought him the thousand pieces of paper.8500:00:03,360 --> 00:00:08,560“I bought him two,” Sabino said, who was poor but optimistic. “I bought him 36, shouted here, who was greedy and haughty.8600:00:08,560 --> 00:00:11,640Pepe went home with 10,000 coins in her backpack8700:00:11,640 --> 00:00:15,080And he fell asleep thinking about his dream of opening a bar.8800:00:15,080 --> 00:00:18,640The next day was Monday and Pepe traveled to the city8900:00:18,640 --> 00:00:22,720and bought wood to build a counter and bought paint.9000:00:22,720 --> 00:00:25,240He went back to his house and got to work.9100:00:05,000 --> 00:00:07,240I mean, I said to Nina,9200:00:07,240 --> 00:00:13,360Pepe didn't find out about the mess he was gonna make because of his little papers.9300:00:13,360 --> 00:00:15,880At that moment in the story I braked9400:00:15,880 --> 00:00:19,320And I stared at my daughter to see if she was understanding the story,9500:00:19,320 --> 00:00:22,800You always have to test metaphors with the boys,9600:00:22,800 --> 00:00:25,040especially when they are complex ideas.9700:00:25,040 --> 00:00:26,560And she said to me, Dad,9800:00:26,560 --> 00:00:29,520This has nothing to do with what the bald man on TV said,9900:00:02,000 --> 00:00:08,000Then I told him what happened in town during the first week.10000:00:09,000 --> 00:00:14,000That Monday, the square was full of people, much more than a normal Monday.10100:00:14,000 --> 00:00:20,000Many neighbors had spent the whole night trimming their own little papers.10200:00:20,000 --> 00:00:23,000because they had also discovered that they had projects10300:00:23,000 --> 00:00:26,000that they could not meet for lack of currency.10400:00:05,600 --> 00:00:09,700Some small pieces of paper said, in short, Horatio’s Eladería. Other papers said Carmen’s hairdressing salon very soon.10500:00:09,700 --> 00:00:13,320And there were even some little papers written by Moncho,10600:00:13,320 --> 00:00:15,680with misspellings, saying,10700:00:15,680 --> 00:00:17,980At the end of the month I will travel to the moon.10800:00:17,980 --> 00:00:22,680Suddenly the neighbors went up to the streetlights of the square,10900:00:22,680 --> 00:00:26,100so that the other neighbors could buy those little papers,11000:00:26,100 --> 00:00:29,980They climbed to the fountain, to exchange paper for coins,11100:00:05,660 --> 00:00:06,660Tuesday was even worse and on Wednesday you could no longer walk through the square of the quilombo that there was.11200:00:11,560 --> 00:00:16,300The mayor had to put in order and enabled a closed place in the municipality so that the neighbors could meet to exchange small papers without destroying the square.11300:00:16,300 --> 00:00:21,800This small place opened on Thursday and was baptized with the name of the Papers Hall.11400:00:22,320 --> 00:00:25,300And so it was that on Friday everyone who had a project11500:00:25,300 --> 00:00: